{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513298","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513298"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:07:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12082"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12082"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.15,0.28,0.29,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4636"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4636","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4636"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12082"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22821"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7038"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14374"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/38352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department (ED) with a four hour history of rapid onset of sharp left flank pain. She has never experienced pain like this before and it is associated with nausea. She has not opened her bowels for the last three days. There is no dysuria, urinary frequency or haematuria. Her medical conditions include stress incontinence and previous inguinal hernia surgery. On examination her blood pressure is 110/90 mmHg, pulse 98/min and temperature 37.2\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her abdomen is soft with normal bowel sounds. Urine dipstick analysis shows a trace of blood. Her serum creatine is 100 mol/L (45-90) and her laboratory values are otherwise normal. A non-contrast CT abdomen/pelvis shows a mild left hydronephrosis and hydroureter and multiple uncomplicated sigmoid diverticula. Whilst in the ED, her pain subsides to a mild discomfort and she does not require any analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Admit for intravenous rehydration","Administer tamsulosin","Renal tract ultrasound in four weeks","Arrange GP follow-up to recheck renal function","Administer eight sachets of macrogol"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture and radiological findings suggest a diagnosis of left ureteric colic. The stone has probably passed spontaneously and the patient should be advised to sieve her urine, looking for the stone. Medical expulsion therapy such as \u003Cstrong\u003Etamsulosin\u003C/strong\u003E is not required as there is no evidence of nephrolithiasis on the CT and the calculus has most likely passed spontaneously. She is now pain-free and provided she is able to tolerate food and fluid intake, \u003Cstrong\u003Eadmission for IV rehydration\u003C/strong\u003E is an unnecessary use of an inpatient bed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Erenal tract ultrasound scan in four weeks\u003C/strong\u003E to check for resolution of hydronephrosis is recommended. If hydronephrosis is still present, then further investigations should be made to exclude malignancy. Likewise, if hydronephrosis is not present, no further investigation is required. If the hydronephrosis is still present, a urological consultation would be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdministering eight sachets of macrogol \u003C/strong\u003Eis not required as this is reserved for patients with faecal impaction. Though the patient may be constipated in this scenario, encouragement of fluids, dietary fibre and short-term over-the-counter laxatives are more appropriate options.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough her creatinine is mildly elevated, a \u003Cstrong\u003Erepeat biochemical screen by her GP\u003C/strong\u003E in a few days\u0027 time will not help determine further management. If a repeat creatinine is normal, it does not rule out hydronephrosis since the contralateral kidney can compensate and if it remains elevated, repeat imaging is recommended nonetheless.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pain-free patients with suspected renal tract calculi can be managed on an out-patient basis if they have normal functioning kidneys and nothing suspicious of infection."],"references":["Leslie SW, Sajjad H, Murphy PB. Renal Calculi. [Updated 2022 May 27]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK442014/","Favus MJ, Feingold KR. Kidney Stone Emergencies. [Updated 2018 Sep 13]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Boyce A, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK278956/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22821"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12082"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"22821","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/22821"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-07-24T11:20:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-10T06:05:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4636"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"38352"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36"